## Which license should I pick?

### AGPLv3 — when you want OSS terms

Pick AGPLv3 if you want a standard, OSI-approved open-source license.

You may use, modify, run, host, and offer Mazemaker as a service —
**but the AGPLv3 will require you to release the entire source code of
your service stack**, including any modifications, to your users
under the same AGPLv3 terms.  This is the same copyleft mechanism that
projects like Plausible Analytics, Mastodon, and Nextcloud use.

If you are building open-source software and willing to license your
own work under the AGPLv3, this is the path for you.

### PolyForm Noncommercial 1.0.0 — when you want a permissive feel without copyleft

Pick PolyForm Noncommercial if you want to use Mazemaker for any
**noncommercial purpose** (research, education, hobby projects,
charitable / public-research / government use, personal study) without
the AGPLv3's copyleft obligations.  No source-disclosure requirement.

The full noncommercial / personal / fair-use definitions are in the
license text (see file above).  In short: if you are not selling, not
operating a paid service, and not using it in the operations of a
for-profit enterprise, you are covered by PolyForm Noncommercial.

### Commercial use

Use that does not fit AGPLv3 (because you are unwilling or unable to
release your source under the AGPLv3) and does not fit PolyForm
Noncommercial (because the use is commercial in nature) **requires a
separate commercial license** from the copyright holder.

To inquire about a commercial license, contact:

> **info@mazemaker.dev**

A commercial license can be drafted to fit specific needs (single
deployment, multi-tenant SaaS, white-label OEM use, embedding in a
commercial product, etc.).  It removes both AGPLv3's copyleft and
PolyForm's noncommercial limit.

